1
00:00:05,381 --> 00:00:12,429
Guru Mahārāj says
‘artha’ translates as ‘meaning’,

2
00:00:12,429 --> 00:00:18,360
‘anartha’ means, 
from another perspective,

3
00:00:18,360 --> 00:00:21,860
‘misconception’, 
the wrong idea.

4
00:00:21,970 --> 00:00:24,778
[Cleansing Consciousness]

5
00:00:25,215 --> 00:00:29,093
So we have the wrong idea
about what Kṛṣṇa consciousness is,

6
00:00:29,093 --> 00:00:33,007
or what is Guru, what is a devotee,
what is Deity.

7
00:00:33,007 --> 00:00:40,518
Everything has to be reconceived.
Reconceptualization.

8
00:00:40,518 --> 00:00:43,946
As Guru Mahārāj says,
“Acquiring the proper angle of vision.”

9
00:00:43,946 --> 00:00:48,277
That’s a lifelong project
for a spiritual practitioner.

10
00:00:48,277 --> 00:00:51,497
It’s not saying,
“Oh, I did that”. No.

11
00:00:51,497 --> 00:00:55,872
It’s, we aspire to that —
cheto-darpaṇa-mārjanaḿ,

12
00:00:55,872 --> 00:01:00,009
how are you going to clearly
reflect upon things

13
00:01:00,009 --> 00:01:03,936
unless a certain amount of cleansing
has taken place?

14
00:01:03,936 --> 00:01:06,605
Cleansing of the consciousness.

15
00:01:06,605 --> 00:01:11,407
Remember, even, interestingly,
when they are doing Gītā promotion

16
00:01:11,407 --> 00:01:14,347
and they quote Thoreau, Emerson,

17
00:01:14,347 --> 00:01:17,159
and all these different people
who appreciated it …

18
00:01:17,159 --> 00:01:21,247
What did Thoreau say,
the American transcendentalist?

19
00:01:21,247 --> 00:01:24,861
Or Emerson, one of the two,
I think it’s Thoreau, he said,

20
00:01:24,861 --> 00:01:29,763
“In the morning I bathe my mind
in the stupendous

21
00:01:29,763 --> 00:01:37,293
cosmogonal glory of Bhagavad-gītā,
in comparison with which

22
00:01:37,293 --> 00:01:42,015
our modern literature
seems puny and trivial.”

23
00:01:42,015 --> 00:01:49,965
So he’s saying, “Every morning I bathe
my intellect with the Bhagavad-gītā.”

24
00:01:50,503 --> 00:01:54,873
It’s a daily cleansing process.

25
00:01:54,873 --> 00:01:56,489
What did Saraswatī Ṭhākur say?

26
00:01:56,489 --> 00:02:01,119
“Beat your mind with a broom
when you wake up.”

27
00:02:01,119 --> 00:02:03,379
And Guru Mahārāj,
the way he said it

28
00:02:03,379 --> 00:02:07,708
—and actually his voice was
practically quivering—he said,

29
00:02:07,708 --> 00:02:12,199
“What have I done?”
(talking about the day before),

30
00:02:12,199 --> 00:02:15,960
“Wasting my life,
wasting my time.

31
00:02:15,960 --> 00:02:19,450
Please, today 
let me do something

32
00:02:19,450 --> 00:02:24,856
of value in service
to Guru and Vaiṣṇava.”

33
00:02:24,856 --> 00:02:27,620
So Saraswatī Ṭhākur’s saying,
“Beat the mind with a broom

34
00:02:27,620 --> 00:02:31,035
a hundred times upon rising,”
and that’s when he said,

35
00:02:31,035 --> 00:02:35,281
“and then do what?
Sing Āmāra jīvana.”

36
00:02:35,281 --> 00:02:39,201
… sadā pāpe rata,
nāhiko punyera leṣa …

37
00:02:39,201 --> 00:02:43,028
Bhakti Vinod, the confessional song,
“This is my life,

38
00:02:43,028 --> 00:02:49,769
there’s no sinful activity I haven’t committed
thousands of times.”

39
00:02:49,769 --> 00:02:53,914
These are the sort of expression
that come out of Bhakti Vinod Ṭhākur

40
00:02:53,914 --> 00:02:58,577
when he’s taking our position.

41
00:02:58,750 --> 00:03:02,012
So Saraswatī Ṭhākur is saying,
“That’s when you sing that.

42
00:03:02,012 --> 00:03:04,319
When you wake up, 
sing that, and say,

43
00:03:04,319 --> 00:03:11,497
‘Let me not waste another day 
where there’s no Vaiṣṇava sevā,

44
00:03:11,497 --> 00:03:17,737
Hari-kathā, dedication.’”

45
00:03:17,737 --> 00:03:21,592
Gurudev said, “You can do
spiritual practices anywhere,

46
00:03:21,592 --> 00:03:24,265
but you don’t get sevā anywhere.”

47
00:03:24,265 --> 00:03:28,165
So when sevā comes to you,
you fight for that

48
00:03:28,165 --> 00:03:31,539
and fight to keep that.

49
00:03:33,483 --> 00:03:40,680
Once he was saying if there was
a fight over his succession

50
00:03:40,680 --> 00:03:44,041
to the point of blood,
to the point of death,

51
00:03:44,041 --> 00:03:47,871
he said, 
“It’s worth fighting for.”

52
00:03:48,221 --> 00:03:49,683
Yes, it’s worth it.

